.SH NAME
Bitcoin::Crypto::Bech32 \- Bech32 implementation
.SH SYNOPSIS
.IX Header "SYNOPSIS"
.Vb 10
\&        # none exported by default
\&        use Bitcoin::Crypto::Bech32 qw(
\&                translate_5to8
\&                translate_8to5
\&                encode_bech32
\&                decode_bech32
\&                encode_segwit
\&                decode_segwit
\&                get_hrp
\&        );
\&
\&        # witness version \- a number from 0 to 16, packed into a byte
\&        my $version = pack \*(AqC\*(Aq, 0;
\&
\&        # human readable part of the address \- a string
\&        my $network_hrp = Bitcoin::Crypto::Network\->get\->segwit_hrp;
\&
\&        # handles Bitcoin SegWit adresses
\&        my $segwit_address = encode_segwit($network_hrp, $version . $pubkeyhash);
\&        my $data_with_version = decode_segwit($segwit_address);
\&
\&        # handles custom Bech32 encoding
\&        # should start with hello1
\&        my $bech32str = encode_bech32(\*(Aqhello\*(Aq, [28, 25, 31, 0, 5], \*(Aqbech32\*(Aq);
\&        my ($hrp, $data_aref, $type) = decode_bech32($bech32str);
.Ve
.SH DESCRIPTION
.IX Header "DESCRIPTION"
Implementation of Bech32 algorithm (BIP\-173 and BIP\-350 compatible)
.PP
The module has a couple of layers of encoding, namely:
.IP \(bu 4
5\-to\-8 and 8\-to\-5 bits transformation
.IP \(bu 4
bech32, which handles checksums and human\-readable (HRP) parts
.IP \(bu 4
segwit, which handles segwit program numbering and validation
.PP
For Bech32\-encoded SegWit addresses, use "encode_segwit" and "decode_segwit".
For custom uses of Bech32 (not in context of Bitcoin SegWit addresses), use
"encode_bech32" and "decode_bech32".
.PP
\&\fBIf in doubt, use segwit functions, not bech32 functions!\fR
.SH FUNCTIONS
.IX Header "FUNCTIONS"
This module is based on Exporter. None of the functions are exported by
default. Use \f(CW\*(C`:all\*(C'\fR tag to import all the functions at once.
.SS encode_segwit
.IX Subsection "encode_segwit"
.SS decode_segwit
.IX Subsection "decode_segwit"
.Vb 1
\&        my $encoded_address = encode_segwit($hrp, $segwit_program);
\&
\&        my $segwit_program = decode_segwit($encoded_address);
.Ve
.PP
Bech32 encoding / decoding valid for SegWit addresses. Human readable part
validation is not included.
.PP
These functions also perform segwit program validation, see
"validate_segwit" in Bitcoin::Crypto::Util.
.PP
Encoding takes two arguments which are a human readable part and a bytestring
(segwit program).
.PP
Decoding takes bech32\-encoded string. Returns the entire encoded data
(bytestring) along with the segwit program version byte.
.PP
Encoding scheme (\f(CW\*(C`bech32\*(C'\fR or \f(CW\*(C`bech32m\*(C'\fR) is chosen based on version included
in the segwit program.
.SS encode_bech32
.IX Subsection "encode_bech32"
.SS decode_bech32
.IX Subsection "decode_bech32"
.Vb 1
\&        my $encoded_bech32 = encode_bech32($hrp, \e@data, $type = \*(Aqbech32m\*(Aq);
\&
\&        my ($hrp, $data_aref, $type) = decode_bech32($encoded_bech32);
.Ve
.PP
Basic bech32 encoding / decoding.
.PP
Encoding takes up to three arguments which are:
.IP \(bu 4
a human readable part
.IP \(bu 4
an array reference of integer values to be encoded in bech32 (each must
be between 0 and 31)
.IP \(bu 4
optional type, which may be \f(CW\*(Aqbech32\*(Aq\fR or \f(CW\*(Aqbech32m\*(Aq\fR (also available
in constant values "BECH32" in Bitcoin::Crypto::Constants and
"BECH32M" in Bitcoin::Crypto::Constants)
.PP
If omitted, the type will be equal to \f(CW\*(Aqbech32m\*(Aq\fR, which has more robust checksum.
.PP
Decoding takes a single parameter: a bech32\-encoded string and returns a list
which has the same values as arguments to \f(CW\*(C`encode_bech32\*(C'\fR function, including
\&\f(CW$type\fR. This means you can feed both bech32 and bech32m encodings to
\&\f(CW\*(C`decode_bech32\*(C'\fR and the function will identify and return the type for you.
.PP
\&\fBThese methods are not meant to work with Bitcoin SegWit addresses, use
\&\fR\f(CB\*(C`encode_segwit\*(C'\fR\fB and \fR\f(CB\*(C`decode_segwit\*(C'\fR\fB for that instead.\fR
.SS translate_5to8
.IX Subsection "translate_5to8"
.SS translate_8to5
.IX Subsection "translate_8to5"
.Vb 1
\&        my $bytestr = translate_5to8(\e@int_array);
\&
\&        my $int_aref = translate_8to5($bytestr);
.Ve
.PP
These are helper functions that implement 5\-bit to 8\-bit encoding used in
bech32 segwit addresses. \f(CW\*(C`translate_8to5\*(C'\fR is used during encoding, and
\&\f(CW\*(C`translate_5to8\*(C'\fR during decoding. They are used as means to store full byte
data in bech32 strings, like so:
.PP
.Vb 3
\&        my $data = encode_bech32(\*(Aqhrp\*(Aq, translate_8to5($bytes));
\&        my @decoded_parts = decode_bech32($data);
\&        my $decoded = translate_5to8($decoded_parts[1]);
.Ve
.SS get_hrp
.IX Subsection "get_hrp"
.Vb 1
\&        $hrp = get_hrp($address)
.Ve
.PP
Returns the human readable part encoded in the bech32 address.
